      "title": "Module 2 — The problem-solving tool",
      "text": "When stress has a cause you can act on, vague worry keeps it spinning; a concrete plan settles it. The structure is simple:\n\n• Name the actual problem in one specific sentence (not \"everything's a mess\" but \"I have three tasks due Friday and no plan\").\n\n• List options: every possible action, even imperfect ones. Quantity first, judgement later.\n\n• Pick one and define the next single step: the smallest thing you can do in the next hour.\n\n• Do that one step. Action shrinks anxiety faster than anything, because anxiety feeds on helplessness, and a step is the opposite of helpless.\n\nYou'll be amazed how much \"stress\" was really just an unmade decision sitting in your chest. The cigarette break used to delay this; now you go straight to the thing that works."
