      "title": "Module 3 — The arousal tools",
      "text": "For the physical side of stress, you have direct levers — no nicotine required:\n\n• Extended exhale breathing. In for 4, out slowly for 6–8, for a minute or two. A longer exhale activates the body's natural brake (the parasympathetic system) and genuinely lowers heart rate. This is the real version of the \"deep drag\" you used to take: except it calms you instead of poisoning you.\n\n• Movement. A two-minute walk, a stretch, a few stairs. Physical movement metabolises stress hormones and resets a racing mind. Smokers got a \"break\" attached to a cigarette; you keep the restorative break and drop the cigarette.\n\n• Grounding. When your mind is spinning, name five things you can see, four you can hear, three you can feel. It pulls you out of the worry loop and back into the present.\n\n• Connection. A two-minute conversation with someone, even unrelated to the stress, settles the nervous system. We're wired to co-regulate.\n\nThese aren't consolation prizes for ex-smokers. They're what genuinely calm, resilient people actually use — and now they're yours."
